Categories of Ubuntu Network Commands
1. Network Configuration

ip       â€“ Modern replacement for `ifconfig`; configure and show IP addresses, routes.
ifconfig â€“ Legacy tool for interface configuration.
nmcli    â€“ Command-line interface for NetworkManager (connect/disconnect Wi-Fi, manage profiles).
iwconfig â€“ Configure wireless interfaces.

2. Connectivity & Testing

ping                       â€“ Test connectivity to a host.
traceroute / tracepath     â€“ Show path packets take to a destination.
curl / wget                â€“ Test HTTP/FTP connectivity and download files.
mtr                        â€“ Combines `ping` and `traceroute` for continuous monitoring.

3. DNS & Name Resolution

nslookup â€“ Query DNS records.
dig      â€“ More advanced DNS lookup tool.
host     â€“ Simple DNS lookup.

4. Network Information

hostname â€“ Display or set system hostname.
arp      â€“ Show ARP table (IP â†” MAC mapping).
ss       - Modern replacement for `netstat`; show socket statistics.
netstat  â€“ Legacy tool for network connections and routing tables.
route    â€“ Show or manipulate routing table.

5. Monitoring & Analysis

iftop    â€“ Real-time bandwidth usage per connection.
nload    â€“ Visual representation of incoming/outgoing traffic.
tcpdump  â€“ Packet capture for analysis.
wireshar (GUI) â€“ Advanced packet analysis.

6. Remote Access

ssh  â€“ Secure remote login.
scp  â€“ Secure file copy.
sftp â€“ Secure FTP.

7. Security & Utilities

ufw      â€“ Uncomplicated Firewall management.
iptables â€“ Advanced firewall and packet filtering.
whois    â€“ Query domain registration info.


